		<h2>Hidden and Ongoing Costs</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Initial testing:</strong> $2,000-$5,000 (HSG, semen analysis, bloodwork, etc.)</li>
			<li><strong>Consultations:</strong> $200-$500 per visit</li>
			<li><strong>Travel:</strong> If your clinic isn't local</li>
			<li><strong>Time off work:</strong> Appointments, procedures, recovery</li>
			<li><strong>Embryo storage:</strong> $500-$1,000 per year ongoing</li>
			<li><strong>Psychological counseling:</strong> Often recommended or required</li>
			<li><strong>Supplements:</strong> Prenatal vitamins, CoQ10, DHEA, etc.</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Insurance Coverage</h2>

		<h3>State Mandates</h3>
		<p>As of 2024, 21 states have fertility insurance laws, but coverage varies:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Comprehensive IVF coverage:</strong> Illinois, Massachusetts, New Jersey, Rhode Island, Maryland, Delaware, Connecticut, Colorado, New York</li>
			<li><strong>Partial coverage:</strong> Arkansas, Hawaii, Montana, Ohio, West Virginia, others</li>
			<li><strong>No mandate:</strong> Most other states</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="info-box">
			<strong>Check Your Policy:</strong> Even in mandated states, not all plans are covered. Self-funded employer plans (common in large companies) are exempt from state mandates. Always verify your specific coverage.
		</div>

		<h3>Common Coverage Limitations</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Lifetime dollar caps or cycle limits</li>
			<li>Exclusion of certain procedures (PGT, ICSI, donor)</li>
			<li>Prior authorization requirements</li>
			<li>In-network clinic requirements</li>
			<li>Documentation of infertility required</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Financial Assistance Options</h2>

		<h3>Clinic Programs</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Multi-cycle packages:</strong> Discounted rates for 2-3 cycles</li>
			<li><strong>Refund programs:</strong> Partial refund if no live birth (higher upfront cost)</li>
			<li><strong>Payment plans:</strong> Interest-free or low-interest financing</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Fertility Loans</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Prosper Healthcare Lending</strong></li>
			<li><strong>CapexMD</strong></li>
			<li><strong>Future Family</strong> - fertility-specific loans</li>
			<li><strong>LendingClub</strong></li>
		</ul>
		<p><em>Interest rates typically range from 5-25% depending on credit.</em></p>

		<h3>Grants and Scholarships</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Baby Quest Foundation</strong> - grants up to $16,000</li>
			<li><strong>The Cade Foundation</strong> - grants up to $10,000</li>
			<li><strong>Pay It Forward Fertility Foundation</strong></li>
			<li><strong>Fertility Within Reach</strong></li>
			<li><strong>The Samfund</strong> - for cancer survivors</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Medication Assistance</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Compassionate Care Program</strong> (EMD Serono) - discounted Gonal-F</li>
			<li><strong>ReUnite Rx</strong> - discounted medications</li>
			<li><strong>Ferring Heart to Heart</strong> - free meds for qualifying patients</li>
			<li><strong>Pharmacy discount cards</strong> and comparison shopping</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Cost-Saving Tips</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Shop around - clinic costs vary significantly</li>
			<li>Ask about cash-pay discounts</li>
			<li>Compare medication prices across pharmacies (specialty, overseas options)</li>
			<li>Consider mini-IVF if appropriate for your situation</li>
			<li>Ask about shared donor egg cycles</li>
			<li>Look into clinical trials at academic centers</li>
			<li>Use FSA/HSA funds (pre-tax savings)</li>
			<li>Review your employer benefits - some offer fertility coverage not required by law</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="success-box">
			<strong>Employer Benefits:</strong> More companies are adding fertility benefits. Check with HR or benefits administrators - some cover $15,000-$50,000+ in lifetime fertility benefits even without state mandates.
		</div>
	</section>
